description: From Latin intersertus, past participle of interserere (“to intersert”), from inter (“between”) + serere (“to join, weave”).

verbs.description: intersert (third-person singular simple present interserts, present participle interserting, simple past and past participle interserted)

entries.meaning: (obsolete, transitive) To put in between other things; to insert.
examples: If I may  […] intersert a short speculation, the depth of the sea  […] is determined in Pliny to be fifteen furlongs.
